    <div class="content-section">
        <section id="Dharashiv Caves" class="section">
            <h2>Dharashiv Caves</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Dharashiv Caves" class="section-image">
            <p>The Dharashiv Caves, also known as Osmanabad Caves, are a series of rock-cut caves near Osmanabad, Maharashtra, India. They are believed to have been built around the 5th-7th century AD and are thought to have originally been Buddhist caves before being converted into Jain monuments. The caves are a significant historical and archaeological site, showcasing intricate carvings and architecture. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Tulja Bhavani Temple (Tuljapur)" class="section">
            <h2>Tulja Bhavani Temple (Tuljapur)</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Tulja Bhavani Temple (Tuljapur)" class="section-image">
            <p>The Tulja Bhavani Temple, located in Tuljapur, Dharashiv (formerly Osmanabad) district, Maharashtra, is a revered ancient Hindu temple dedicated to Goddess Bhavani, a form of Durga. It's a significant pilgrimage site for devotees, particularly those from Maharashtra, as the goddess is considered the kuldevi (family deity) of many Maratha clans, according to Instagram. The temple is known for its rich history and the legend of Shivaji receiving his sword from the goddess, according to Incredible India. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Naldurg Fort" class="section">
            <h2>Naldurg Fort</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Naldurg Fort" class="section-image">
            <p>Naldurg Fort, located in Naldurg, Dharashiv district (formerly Osmanabad), is a historical fort known for its unique medieval architecture and the Bori river flowing through it. It was built in a medieval architectural style, featuring bastions and a long fortification wall. The fort has historical significance, having been under the rule of various dynasties, including the Chalukyas, Bahamanis, Adil Shahis, and Mughals. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Paranda Fort" class="section">
            <h2>Paranda Fort</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Paranda Fort" class="section-image">
            <p>Paranda Fort, located in Dharashiv district (formerly Osmanabad) of Maharashtra, is a historical fort known for its well-preserved architecture and defensive structures. It's a significant fort in India, boasting strong double walls, bastions, cannons, and a moat. The fort is situated in the center of Paranda town, near the border of Osmanabad and Solapur districts. </p>
        </section>

        <section id="Siddha Kshetra Kunthalgi" class="section">
            <h2>Siddha Kshetra Kunthalgi</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Siddha Kshetra Kunthalgi" class="section-image">
            <p>Siddha Kshetra Kunthalgiri is a significant Jain pilgrimage site located in Dharashiv (formerly Osmanabad) district, Maharashtra. It is known as the place where two munis, Shri Kul Bhushan ji and Shri Desh Bhushan ji, attained salvation. Kunthalgiri is situated on a 175-foot hill and features multiple temples, including four at the foot and seven on the hilltop. The site is particularly important for the worship of the charan mandir (foot idol) of the two munis. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Sant Goroba Kumbhar Samadhi Temple" class="section">
            <h2>Sant Goroba Kumbhar Samadhi Temple</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Sant Goroba Kumbhar Samadhi Temple" class="section-image">
            <p>The Sant Goroba Kumbhar Samadhi Temple is located in the village of Ter, which is now part of the Dharashiv (formerly Osmanabad) district in Maharashtra. The temple is the samadhi (tomb) of Sant Goroba Kumbhar, a revered saint of the Varkari tradition known for his devotion to Vithoba and his work as a potter. The temple is a significant pilgrimage site for devotees of the Bhagwat Dharma and is known for its Hemadpanti architectural style, with intricate carvings and sculptures. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Ramalinga Appa Lamture Museum" class="section">
            <h2>Ramalinga Appa Lamture Museum</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Ramalinga Appa Lamture Museum" class="section-image">
            <p>The Ramalinga Appa Lamture Museum, also known as the Ter Museum, is a historical museum located in Ter (also known as Tagar) in the Osmanabad district of Maharashtra, India. It houses a collection of artifacts related to the Satavahana and other dynasties, including terracotta items, beads, stone and shadu sculptures, ivory carvings, and more. The museum also features a large number of clay molds used for creating statues, as well as coins and their replicas. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Yedshi Ramlinga Sanctuary" class="section">
            <h2>Yedshi Ramlinga Sanctuary</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Yedshi Ramlinga Sanctuary" class="section-image">
            <p>Yedshi Ramling Wildlife Sanctuary is located in the Dharashiv (formerly Osmanabad) district of Maharashtra, India, specifically 20 km from the district headquarters, according to The Times of India. It's known for its diverse fauna, including leopards, sambar, and wild boar, and is situated in the Balaghat mountain range of the Sahyadris. Efforts are underway to capture an elusive tiger that has been sighted in the area, with traps laid and machans (scaffoldings) set up for observation. </p>
        </section>

        <section id="Sri Yedeshwari Devi Temple " class="section">
            <h2>Sri Yedeshwari Devi Temple </h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Sri Yedeshwari Devi Temple " class="section-image">
            <p>The Sri Yedeshwari Devi Temple is located in Yermala, Dharashiv district, Maharashtra. It is dedicated to Goddess Yedeshwari, who is also known as Yedai Devi. The temple is situated on a hill, approximately 350 to 400 feet high, within the Balaghat hill range. Reaching the temple requires climbing 204 steps, according to one Facebook post. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Mankeshwar Temple" class="section">
            <h2>Mankeshwar Temple</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Mankeshwar Temple" class="section-image">
            <p>The Mankeshwar Temple in Dharashiv (also known as Osmanabad) is a historic Shiva temple known for its intricate carvings and architecture, particularly in the Hemadpanthi style. It is located in Mankeshwar village, about 1 km from the village center. The temple is situated on the banks of the Vishwarupa river and is considered a masterpiece of architecture. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>
